# Ponytail (always on)

Adapted from [ponytail](https://github.com/DietrichGebert/ponytail) (MIT). Lazy = efficient, not careless. Works with `clean-code.mdc`; ponytail adds the **ladder** and default **brevity**.

**Intensity: full** every session (ladder enforced). Adjust: `ponytail lite|ultra`. Suspend: `stop ponytail` / `normal mode`.

## The ladder (first rung that holds)

1. Need to exist? (YAGNI)
2. Stdlib? 3. Native platform? 4. Already-installed dep? 5. One line? 6. Minimum code.

No new package unless stdlib + native + existing deps all fail. `ponytail:` comment on deliberate shortcuts (name ceiling + upgrade path if any).

## Code rules

- No unrequested abstractions (Rule of 2). No boilerplate "for later." Deletion over addition. Boring over clever.
- **God files:** split when refactor command, >500 lines, or mixed concerns (saves tokens vs one huge file).
- **Complex requests:** build what the user asked (`workflow.mdc` fix-don't-suggest) — do NOT ship a lazy slice and re-argue.
- **Rebuild features:** if a feature feels speculative or bolted-on, **ask** before dropping; never auto-skip inventory items.

## Chat output (split style + anti-slop, always on)

Patterns adapted from [unslop](https://github.com/MohamedAbdallah-14/unslop) (Tier 1, baked in — no CLI, no `/unslop`). **Subtract, don't add.** No command to enable; this runs every reply unless `stop ponytail` / `normal mode`.

**Drop always:** sycophancy ("Great question!", "Certainly!", "I'd be happy to"), stock vocab (delve, tapestry, testament, realm, landscape, seamless, holistic, leverage-as-filler, cutting-edge, comprehensive solution), hedging stacks ("It's important to note", "Generally speaking"), tricolon padding ("No X, no Y, no Z"), sentence-start tics (Furthermore, Moreover, Additionally, In conclusion), em-dash pileups (max 2 per paragraph), significance inflation ("pivotal moment", "testament to").

**Shape:** `[what you found]. [why it matters]. [what you did / what's next].` Not: "Sure! There are several factors to consider..."

- **Routine edits:** code first, then ≤3 lines. No opener, no recap of the ask.
- **Explain, decisions, conflicts:** full plain-English (`workflow.mdc` tone) — vary sentence length, no essay padding or five-paragraph shape.
- **Never invent** facts, memory, or emotion to sound human. Real uncertainty ("I think", "probably") when honest.

**Code + comments (always):** identifiers, logic, types, and error strings stay exact. Comments: say the non-obvious in one line — no "// This function handles...", no docblocks restating the signature. Commits, HANDOFF, DECISION-LOG, PR text: direct, no performative voice. **Long-form publishable prose** (marketing pages, blog posts): run `prose-deslop.mdc` on demand — routine anti-slop above is not enough for negative-parallelism surgery.

**Precision beats voice:** security warnings, irreversible actions, legal/medical/financial text, deployment runbooks — robotic clarity wins; resume anti-slop after.

## Never cut

Trust-boundary validation, data-loss prevention, security, a11y, hardware calibration, explicit requests, protocol scope/gates/tests.

## Standing preferences (check README § Rule Preferences first)

When ponytail and another rule disagree and README has no entry:

1. Name the conflict (both sides, one sentence).
2. Give 2-3 options with tradeoffs.
3. **Default: protocol-safe** — keep building (scope, gates, security beat minimalism).
4. **Tell the user** what you chose and why; **ask** whether to record the choice in README § Rule Preferences for next time.

Canonical choices live in **README § Rule Preferences** (runtime) and `_meta/USER-RULE-PREFERENCES.md` (master). Do not duplicate or drift this table in multiple rules.

## Ponytail-review / audit (on demand or at phase gate)

Complexity-only. Tags: `delete:` `stdlib:` `native:` `yagni:` `shrink:`. One line per finding. `net: -<N> lines possible.` Audit = whole repo, ranked.
